07059nam a22009855i 9783110702217DE-B159720210526051534.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210526t20202021gw     fo  d z      eng d  a2020938291  a97831107022177 a10.1515/97831107022172doi  a(DE-B1597)549605  a(OCoLC)1206401959  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 7aLIT0041902bisacsh00aWisdom, Love, and Friendship in Ancient Greek Philosophy :bEssays in Honor of Daniel Devereux /ced. by Georgia Sermamoglou-Soulmaidi, Evan Robert Keeling. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2020] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (X, 351 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aBeiträge zur Altertumskunde ;v39100tFrontmatter -- tTable of Contents -- tIntroduction -- tPart I Plato -- t1 Of Mice and Men: Socrates on Wisdom and Good Fortune in Plato’s Euthydemus -- t2 Friendship and Rhetoric in Plato’s Gorgias -- t3 Odi et Amo: Socrates and Callicles -- t4 Love in Plato’s Alcibiades -- t5 The Spatial Erotics of Plato’s Symposium -- t6 The Telos Puzzle in Plato’s Symposium -- t7 Socrates’ Critique of Writing in Plato’s Phaedrus -- t8 Socrates, Philosophy, and Friendship in the Phaedo -- t9 Recollection and Innatism in the Phaedo -- tPart II Aristotle and the Epicureans -- t10 Phronêsis: Aristotle on Moral Wisdom and its Origins in Philia -- t11 Φιλοσοφητέον: One Must Philosophize -- t12 De l’amitié politique chez Aristote -- t13 Friendship in Aristotle’s Magna Moralia -- t14 Epicurean Friendship and the Therapy of Grief Subject Index (Including Ancient Authors and Works) -- tSubject Index (Including Ancient Authors and Works) -- tIndex of Modern Authors0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis volume consists of fourteen essays in honor of Daniel Devereux on the themes of love, friendship, and wisdom in Plato, Aristotle, and the Epicureans. Philia (friendship) and eros (love) are topics of major philosophical interest in ancient Greek philosophy. They are also topics of growing interest and importance in contemporary philosophy, much of which is inspired by ancient discussions. Philosophy is itself, of course, a special sort of love, viz. the love of wisdom. Loving in the right way is very closely connected to doing philosophy, cultivating wisdom, and living well. The first nine essays run the gamut of Plato's philosophical career. They include discussions of the ›Alcibiades‹, ›Euthydemus‹, ›Gorgias‹, ›Phaedo‹, ›Phaedrus‹, and ›Symposium‹. The next four essays turn to Aristotle and include treatments of the ›Nicomachean Ethics‹ and ›Politics‹ as well as the lesser-known works ›Protrepticus‹ and ›Magna Moralia‹. The volume ends with friendship in the Epicureans. As a whole, the volume brings out the centrality of love and friendship for the conception of the philosophical life held by the ancients. The book should appeal to anyone interested in these works or in the topics of love, friendship, or wisdom.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 4aAncient Greek Philosophy. 4aAristotle. 4aEpicureans. 4aPlato. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Ancient & Classical.2bisacsh1 aBeer, Andrew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBolton, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDoyle, James, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFerejohn, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFine, Gail, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGill, Mary Louise, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIrwin, T. H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKeeling, Evan Robert, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabu